WEBVTT

00:00:00.010 --> 00:00:02.400
- Let's welcome Arushi, everybody.

00:00:02.410 --> 00:00:03.700
- Thanks, everyone.

00:00:03.710 --> 00:00:09.840
I feel like I can't see over my computer.

00:00:09.850 --> 00:00:13.670
Yeah, my name is Arushi, and I'm a

00:00:13.670 --> 00:00:17.090
founder and CEO of Habitat, and today I'm gonna

00:00:17.090 --> 00:00:19.320
be talking about why we're building Habitat.

00:00:19.330 --> 00:00:22.260
Is everything okay?

00:00:22.270 --> 00:00:24.940
Okay, cool.

00:00:24.950 --> 00:00:28.390
I believe that App Protocol gives us a chance to fundamentally reim

00:00:28.390 --> 00:00:32.210
agine what connecting with each other online means, and through that

00:00:32.210 --> 00:00:34.460
process, rewilding the internet.

00:00:34.470 --> 00:00:37.820
So, I'm gonna try to get this right.

00:00:37.830 --> 00:00:39.310
Okay.

00:00:39.510 --> 00:00:41.000
It's a loose agenda.

00:00:41.130 --> 00:00:44.050
In this talk, I start with some questions, talk about

00:00:44.050 --> 00:00:47.020
my dreams for the web, and use some quotes from writers

00:00:47.180 --> 00:00:49.160
I appreciate to guide my thinking.

00:00:49.170 --> 00:00:54.540
Okay, cool.

00:00:54.550 --> 00:00:57.570
So, if you go to approto.

00:00:57.570 --> 00:01:00.180
com, this is what the website looks like.

00:01:00.190 --> 00:01:02.800
The first time I read this, I kind of had the

00:01:02.800 --> 00:01:05.040
question, what actually is the social internet?

00:01:05.050 --> 00:01:09.080
The term, the social internet, came around before my time

00:01:09.080 --> 00:01:10.920
, and even though I've heard it many times, I

00:01:10.920 --> 00:01:14.810
never reflected deeply on what it meant, or what it referred

00:01:14.810 --> 00:01:15.170
to.

00:01:15.190 --> 00:01:23.550
So, this is what the internet does, right

00:01:23.550 --> 00:01:24.260
?

00:01:24.290 --> 00:01:26.320
It connects two computers together.

00:01:26.330 --> 00:01:29.420
So, my question was, how can the internet not be

00:01:29.420 --> 00:01:30.320
inherently social?

00:01:30.330 --> 00:01:33.880
Why is the social internet separate from the internet itself?

00:01:33.890 --> 00:01:39.320
Of course, this is not exactly how the internet works.

00:01:39.330 --> 00:01:42.040
It connects in order for two computers to share data with each

00:01:42.040 --> 00:01:42.520
other.

00:01:42.530 --> 00:01:44.460
Typically, they connect to a shared server.

00:01:44.470 --> 00:01:52.540
Which could be across the ocean, and that is how you

00:01:52.600 --> 00:01:54.600
get a platform.

00:01:54.610 --> 00:01:55.600
Boo.

00:01:55.610 --> 00:01:59.600
Sorry about this.

00:01:59.610 --> 00:02:03.240
So, as I started to read more about this time before

00:02:03.240 --> 00:02:08.160
myself, when the internet transitioned from unsocial to social,

00:02:08.170 --> 00:02:10.740
what I realized is that when people use the term the social

00:02:10.740 --> 00:02:14.840
internet, what they actually mean is the platform internet.

00:02:14.850 --> 00:02:16.850
When the web transitioned from web 1.

00:02:16.850 --> 00:02:17.900
0 to web 2.

00:02:17.900 --> 00:02:21.010
0, it allowed users to publish pieces of data, including

00:02:21.010 --> 00:02:24.550
social data, and platforms were the primary way to do so

00:02:24.550 --> 00:02:24.860
.

00:02:24.870 --> 00:02:27.440
And to be fair, several of the articles I read were

00:02:27.440 --> 00:02:28.300
by Kyle Chayka.

00:02:28.310 --> 00:02:31.020
So, maybe it is Kyle pushing this agenda.

00:02:31.030 --> 00:02:33.800
But I think, generally speaking, what people imagine when you

00:02:33.800 --> 00:02:38.810
use the term the social internet is platforms like earlier MySpace

00:02:38.810 --> 00:02:41.230
AOL in the first era, and now we have like

00:02:41.230 --> 00:02:45.760
X, Facebook, Instagram, even Blue Sky and Black Sky

00:02:45.760 --> 00:02:46.260
.

00:02:46.270 --> 00:02:50.360
When people use the term social internet, what they typically mean

00:02:50.370 --> 00:02:55.600
are billion user social media platforms.

00:02:55.610 --> 00:02:58.500
But I don't think that's what the social internet is

00:02:58.500 --> 00:03:00.160
or what it can be.

00:03:00.170 --> 00:03:04.460
And I think app protocol gives us the chance to imagine beyond

00:03:04.460 --> 00:03:05.100
that.

00:03:05.110 --> 00:03:07.900
Okay, sorry.

00:03:07.910 --> 00:03:08.770
So, Ursula M.

00:03:08.770 --> 00:03:12.540
Franklin is a Canadian scientist who, in 1989, gave a

00:03:12.540 --> 00:03:15.960
series of lectures titled The Real World of Technology.

00:03:15.970 --> 00:03:18.120
In it, she talks about how technology is not just the

00:03:18.120 --> 00:03:21.070
technological artifact that we put out into the world, but also

00:03:21.070 --> 00:03:24.120
how it affects the world, which in turn affects new technologies

00:03:24.120 --> 00:03:24.360
.

00:03:24.370 --> 00:03:26.740
This is kind of like the feedback loop that Rudy from Black

00:03:26.740 --> 00:03:29.260
Sky was talking about yesterday in his talk.

00:03:29.270 --> 00:03:32.120
So, Ursula says, "As I see it,

00:03:32.120 --> 00:03:35.060
technology has built the house in which we all live.

00:03:35.070 --> 00:03:38.120
The house is continually being extended and remodeled.

00:03:38.130 --> 00:03:41.220
More and more of human life takes place within its walls,

00:03:41.220 --> 00:03:44.260
so that today there is hardly any human activity that does not

00:03:44.260 --> 00:03:45.960
occur within this house.

00:03:45.970 --> 00:03:48.100
We all are affected by the design of the house, the

00:03:48.100 --> 00:03:53.010
division of its space, and the location of its doors and

00:03:53.010 --> 00:03:57.370
walls." That was written in 1989, but I think it

00:03:57.370 --> 00:04:00.200
's clear where I'm going with this metaphor.

00:04:00.210 --> 00:04:02.720
The internet is the house we live in.

00:04:02.730 --> 00:04:05.500
We are all affected by the, hopefully it's playing,

00:04:05.500 --> 00:04:08.200
the division of its space, the location of its doors and

00:04:08.200 --> 00:04:11.180
walls, and how it is continually remodeled.

00:04:11.190 --> 00:04:13.370
And I think that's why the artist Spencer Chang's work

00:04:13.370 --> 00:04:16.520
resonates with a lot of people because it makes the movement through

00:04:16.650 --> 00:04:21.150
this internet house visible when it is so often invisible or goes

00:04:21.150 --> 00:04:26.860
completely unnoticed by us.

00:04:26.870 --> 00:04:29.450
So if that is the case, if the internet is now

00:04:29.450 --> 00:04:31.890
the house we all live in, then what is the role

00:04:31.890 --> 00:04:33.540
of technologists?

00:04:33.550 --> 00:04:35.580
The way I see it, we build not only the house

00:04:35.580 --> 00:04:38.420
, but we also dictate how the house gets built, and

00:04:38.420 --> 00:04:42.000
by whom, through things like standards and protocols.

00:04:42.010 --> 00:04:44.830
And the decisions we make not only affect the internet itself,

00:04:44.830 --> 00:04:47.780
but also reshape our physical reality, as in the case

00:04:47.880 --> 00:04:50.920
of airspace, a term that's also coined by our

00:04:50.920 --> 00:04:54.810
friend Kyle Cheka, to refer to how the platform Instagram

00:04:54.810 --> 00:04:58.970
caused cafes and restaurants to all merge into a homogenous aesthetic

00:04:58.970 --> 00:04:59.220
.

00:04:59.230 --> 00:05:04.680
Okay, so there's this thing I say, which is

00:05:04.680 --> 00:05:09.980
I want to make app protocol the default way to build on

00:05:09.980 --> 00:05:10.980
the web.

00:05:10.990 --> 00:05:12.900
And when I say that, I don't necessarily mean app

00:05:12.910 --> 00:05:13.840
protocol of today.

00:05:13.850 --> 00:05:16.960
I mean whatever future iteration of app protocol it is that actually

00:05:16.960 --> 00:05:19.940
enables this to be the case.

00:05:19.950 --> 00:05:22.160
And many of you in this room might be agreeing with me

00:05:22.160 --> 00:05:30.950
, but the question we should really be asking

00:05:30.950 --> 00:05:38.100
is why.

00:05:38.110 --> 00:05:41.110
What real world conditions am I trying to create by making this

00:05:41.110 --> 00:05:45.500
statement, or rather, what is the house that I'm

00:05:45.510 --> 00:05:47.440
trying to build?

00:05:47.450 --> 00:05:50.160
And these are questions that we must answer.

00:05:50.170 --> 00:05:53.390
So Lawrence Hoff, who I think is here, wrote in

00:05:53.390 --> 00:05:57.000
a recent essay that in the older protocols of the web,

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:00.420
the silence about purpose was a politics of non-interference

00:06:00.420 --> 00:06:00.680
.

00:06:00.690 --> 00:06:05.210
And this led to governance being controlled by whichever actor had the

00:06:05.210 --> 00:06:06.520
most resources.

00:06:06.530 --> 00:06:08.070
So I think it's great that as an ecosystem we are

00:06:08.150 --> 00:06:11.360
already asking some of these hard questions.

00:06:11.370 --> 00:06:15.060
Yeah, so I was trying to find the article by Lang

00:06:15.060 --> 00:06:17.640
don Winner, do artifacts have politics?

00:06:17.650 --> 00:06:21.360
And I just thought this was funny.

00:06:21.370 --> 00:06:24.840
It's 2026.

00:06:24.850 --> 00:06:27.990
We know that artifacts do have politics, and not just because

00:06:27.990 --> 00:06:30.800
the AI overview is telling us.

00:06:30.810 --> 00:06:33.600
Rather than shy away from dealing with the realities of our jobs

00:06:33.600 --> 00:06:36.180
, I think we should get really clear on what we are

00:06:36.220 --> 00:06:37.840
trying to build and why.

00:06:37.850 --> 00:06:40.820
On the power dynamics encoded in what we build, and

00:06:40.820 --> 00:06:45.540
on the types of conditions that those give rise to.

00:06:45.550 --> 00:06:49.170
Okay, so in this talk, I'm going to pitch

00:06:49.170 --> 00:06:52.180
a possible vision for the internet.

00:06:52.190 --> 00:06:55.050
Ruha Benjamin in her recent book said, "Those who

00:06:55.050 --> 00:06:59.090
monopolize resources also monopolize imagination." So I think it

00:06:59.090 --> 00:07:02.260
's important for us to recognize that the current internet constrains

00:07:02.260 --> 00:07:07.430
what we imagine and collectively resist that in order to imagine alternative

00:07:07.430 --> 00:07:08.300
futures.

00:07:08.310 --> 00:07:16.380
So in my internet, we are not followed wherever we

00:07:16.440 --> 00:07:17.030
go.

00:07:17.050 --> 00:07:20.280
Platform dynamics make tracking possible because the two computers must use an

00:07:20.280 --> 00:07:22.080
intermediary server.

00:07:22.090 --> 00:07:29.740
Hence the whole field of peer-to-peer.

00:07:29.750 --> 00:07:33.680
We can be highly contextual in our interactions.

00:07:33.690 --> 00:07:36.170
For example, I might not use Slack for both my workplace

00:07:36.170 --> 00:07:41.840
messaging app and my organizing work and talking with friends the way

00:07:41.840 --> 00:07:45.940
I do today in a flattened context.

00:07:45.970 --> 00:07:48.460
The things we do are also human-sized and human shapes

00:07:48.460 --> 00:07:48.680
.

00:07:48.690 --> 00:07:51.470
So here, I'm thinking a lot about Aaron Kass

00:07:51.470 --> 00:07:55.060
ane's idea of oversaturation and how the bodily experience

00:07:55.070 --> 00:07:58.720
or affect of using the social internet today is not really conduc

00:07:58.720 --> 00:08:00.620
ive to a living human being.

00:08:00.630 --> 00:08:06.560
Oh, let's get the slide.

00:08:06.570 --> 00:08:10.750
And these conditions that I described are radically different than what we

00:08:10.760 --> 00:08:12.560
experience today.

00:08:12.570 --> 00:08:15.020
So we don't know what it feels like to have that

00:08:15.020 --> 00:08:16.560
internet or to live in that internet house.

00:08:16.570 --> 00:08:24.230
And I think changing those conditions is what fundamentally gets us past

00:08:24.230 --> 00:08:26.230
skeuomorphism.

00:08:26.330 --> 00:08:29.340
So we can't just throw new products into being that are

00:08:29.340 --> 00:08:32.220
non-skeuomorphic without first changing the conditions

00:08:32.220 --> 00:08:35.650
that cause people to actually make them useful and needed in the

00:08:35.650 --> 00:08:36.560
first place.

00:08:36.570 --> 00:08:45.030
So that's kind of like the hard

00:08:45.070 --> 00:08:53.560
part is the direction setting

00:08:53.560 --> 00:08:54.440
.

00:08:54.470 --> 00:08:56.600
And that's why the older protocol has had a politics of

00:08:56.600 --> 00:08:59.400
non-interference because it's hard to do this.

00:08:59.410 --> 00:09:01.700
It's easier to step back and say this is just a

00:09:01.700 --> 00:09:02.500
protocol.

00:09:02.510 --> 00:09:04.470
But once we do that, we can articulate what we need

00:09:04.470 --> 00:09:08.600
to build and therefore what the protocol needs to provide.

00:09:08.610 --> 00:09:12.680
So the internet of my dreams can only exist if there is

00:09:12.680 --> 00:09:15.220
no data hoarding by default.

00:09:15.230 --> 00:09:18.110
So like the easiest way to build on the web is privacy

00:09:18.110 --> 00:09:19.080
preserving.

00:09:19.090 --> 00:09:20.540
This is not the case today.

00:09:20.550 --> 00:09:25.720
In order to serve a social experience, you need to store

00:09:25.720 --> 00:09:27.020
user data.

00:09:27.030 --> 00:09:30.330
I believe the types of software and user experiences that are delivered

00:09:30.330 --> 00:09:34.380
on the social internet today are limited because it's software engineers

00:09:34.380 --> 00:09:36.240
and tech companies building them.

00:09:36.250 --> 00:09:38.480
When people talk about web 1.

00:09:38.480 --> 00:09:41.600
0 and what feels like to me the glory era of the

00:09:41.600 --> 00:09:44.560
internet, they talk about how what drew people to the web

00:09:44.560 --> 00:09:47.690
was the fact that so many different types of people, technical

00:09:47.690 --> 00:09:50.440
and non-technical, were creating websites.

00:09:50.450 --> 00:09:55.990
I think we need to do the same thing for web 2

00:09:55.990 --> 00:09:56.440
.

00:09:56.440 --> 00:09:56.960
0.

00:09:56.970 --> 00:10:00.370
And then reflecting on the idea of what it means for the

00:10:00.370 --> 00:10:02.970
web to be human shaped, I think a big part of

00:10:03.050 --> 00:10:06.430
what is missing on the internet is this idea of communities or

00:10:06.430 --> 00:10:10.570
groups as a first principle rather than using platforms to then build

00:10:10.570 --> 00:10:12.920
relationships or communities on top.

00:10:12.930 --> 00:10:20.720
Okay, so what does this mean for the protocol?

00:10:20.730 --> 00:10:25.320
I think an iteration of the protocol that enables this should support

00:10:25.320 --> 00:10:26.920
privacy by design and default.

00:10:26.930 --> 00:10:35.390
should be usable

00:10:35.440 --> 00:10:39.790
, maintainable, extendable beyond protocol people and should be

00:10:39.800 --> 00:10:43.440
flexible enough to support group self-management.

00:10:43.450 --> 00:10:46.400
So I really believe in this idea of leveling up people rather

00:10:46.400 --> 00:10:48.440
than dumbing down technology.

00:10:48.450 --> 00:10:54.100
Okay, so all of this stuff is what I think about

00:10:54.100 --> 00:10:58.800
every day, what my collaborators and I at Habitat think

00:10:58.800 --> 00:10:59.960
about every day.

00:10:59.970 --> 00:11:03.320
And it's funny because even though I think about it,

00:11:03.320 --> 00:11:06.840
writing this talk really clarified to me what Habitat's mission

00:11:06.840 --> 00:11:09.840
is as reimagining the social internet.

00:11:09.850 --> 00:11:18.100
Okay, so

00:11:18.130 --> 00:11:20.770
at Habitat, we are trying to lower the barrier of

00:11:20.770 --> 00:11:23.000
who can build on the social internet.

00:11:23.010 --> 00:11:28.600
Sorry, I can never find that.

00:11:28.610 --> 00:11:36.600
One, no.

00:11:36.610 --> 00:11:40.750
In the traditional web, people who build platforms create the social

00:11:40.750 --> 00:11:41.600
internet.

00:11:41.610 --> 00:11:44.350
App Proto changes this with PDS's, custom feeds

00:11:44.350 --> 00:11:47.640
, and other levers to tweak experiences on platforms.

00:11:47.650 --> 00:11:50.600
But to build a new type of social experience or modality

00:11:50.600 --> 00:11:53.680
, often times you still need to build an app view.

00:11:53.690 --> 00:11:56.300
Habitat wants to see if we can go even further.

00:11:56.310 --> 00:11:59.540
What kinds of protocol level or shared infrastructure do we need to

00:11:59.540 --> 00:12:02.120
make it as easy to build a social experience as it is

00:12:02.120 --> 00:12:03.300
to build a website?

00:12:06.610 --> 00:12:15.170
We believe building the social internet should not require sacrificing user privacy

00:12:15.170 --> 00:12:15.600
.

00:12:15.610 --> 00:12:19.170
So one step we are taking in this direction is trying to

00:12:19.170 --> 00:12:21.600
give users agency over this data.

00:12:21.610 --> 00:12:24.570
So in Habitat, you can see and say who as

00:12:24.570 --> 00:12:28.670
people or both apps have access to parts of your data,

00:12:28.670 --> 00:12:30.350
and we are trying to give people a way to search over

00:12:30.350 --> 00:12:31.600
all their data in one place.

00:12:31.610 --> 00:12:35.860
Which is something you should be able to do today on the

00:12:35.860 --> 00:12:38.600
web but is pretty much impossible.

00:12:38.610 --> 00:12:45.460
Okay, and then third, we are thinking about this community

00:12:45.460 --> 00:12:46.600
piece.

00:12:46.610 --> 00:12:48.700
So, I quit my job at Figma a month ago

00:12:48.700 --> 00:12:50.600
to work full time on Habitat.

00:12:50.610 --> 00:12:56.310
And one thing I think about is how at Figma,

00:12:56.310 --> 00:13:03.600
the tools I primarily used were Slack, Google Suite, and

00:13:03.600 --> 00:13:03.600
Zoom.

00:13:03.610 --> 00:13:07.180
I'm a part of this wonderful organization called Collective Action

00:13:07.180 --> 00:13:11.060
School, and it's an experimental school for tech workers to

00:13:11.060 --> 00:13:12.600
reshape the industry from inside of it.

00:13:12.610 --> 00:13:16.930
So there, the primary tools we used to communicate are also

00:13:16.930 --> 00:13:19.600
Slack, Google Suite, and Zoom.

00:13:19.610 --> 00:13:22.360
And when building Habitat, the easiest tools to reach for

00:13:22.360 --> 00:13:24.600
were also Slack, Google Suite, and Zoom.

00:13:24.610 --> 00:13:27.790
So when I think about data agency and self-determination

00:13:27.790 --> 00:13:31.430
for groups, but specifically Collective Action School as a community

00:13:31.430 --> 00:13:34.220
, my goal and what we're really trying to build at

00:13:34.220 --> 00:13:38.030
Habitat is that communities can create their own spaces for their

00:13:38.030 --> 00:13:42.170
own context, rather than have to use a particular platform for

00:13:42.170 --> 00:13:44.600
a particular tool or use case.

00:13:44.610 --> 00:13:49.110
So I imagine possibly building something like this for Collective Action

00:13:49.110 --> 00:13:51.780
School, where we have our public-facing website, but

00:13:51.780 --> 00:13:54.120
when you log in, there's a space that's members

00:13:54.120 --> 00:13:54.600
only.

00:13:54.610 --> 00:13:58.840
And it doesn't look like any other chat or syllabus or

00:13:58.840 --> 00:14:03.180
schedule like any other space on the internet, because it's

00:14:03.180 --> 00:14:05.600
made specifically for Collective Action School.

00:14:05.610 --> 00:14:08.600
Okay, cool.

00:14:08.610 --> 00:14:12.300
I wouldn't be a good CEO without a little shameless plug

00:14:12.300 --> 00:14:12.600
.

00:14:12.610 --> 00:14:16.760
So we do have a version of permission data that actually looks

00:14:16.760 --> 00:14:19.600
quite similar to what the Blue Sky team put out, I

00:14:19.600 --> 00:14:22.600
think, and will be forwards compatible with what they do.

00:14:22.610 --> 00:14:25.590
So if you have use cases for permission data, we'd

00:14:25.590 --> 00:14:26.600
love to chat.

00:14:26.610 --> 00:14:29.310
And we've been building out products on top of our permission

00:14:29.310 --> 00:14:32.600
data and other tools and services to show what you can do

00:14:32.600 --> 00:14:33.600
with Habitat.

00:14:33.610 --> 00:14:36.120
Our first toy app is Docs, if people want to

00:14:36.120 --> 00:14:37.600
play around with that.

00:14:37.610 --> 00:14:40.910
But we're also building out a control plane to actually see

00:14:40.910 --> 00:14:46.080
what it looks like for users to have agency and transparency into

00:14:46.160 --> 00:14:47.600
their data.

00:14:47.610 --> 00:14:52.600
Thanks.

00:14:52.610 --> 00:14:58.600
Okay, but back to the title of the talk.

00:14:58.610 --> 00:15:02.010
In ecology, rewilding is a process where humans

00:15:02.010 --> 00:15:06.040
do an initial intervention in a given place or land in order

00:15:06.040 --> 00:15:07.600
to restore the ecosystem.

00:15:07.610 --> 00:15:11.830
And the hope is that these seeds of intervention will seed natural

00:15:11.830 --> 00:15:14.600
processes and increase biodiversity.

00:15:14.610 --> 00:15:17.240
So I think in a lot of ways that our work as

00:15:17.240 --> 00:15:21.660
developers in and of this protocol is to make these little seeds

00:15:21.660 --> 00:15:24.420
of intervention on the web in order to enable others to use

00:15:24.420 --> 00:15:27.330
and build on the web as a sort of natural and organic

00:15:27.330 --> 00:15:28.600
process on its own.

00:15:28.610 --> 00:15:34.250
So I care about all of these things, but I really

00:15:34.250 --> 00:15:40.780
care about the second point that builders on a protocol and on

00:15:40.780 --> 00:15:44.970
the web for social experiences shouldn't just be software engineers and

00:15:44.970 --> 00:15:49.580
companies.

00:15:49.610 --> 00:15:55.480
This idea of biodiversity or diversity in general comes up not just

00:15:55.480 --> 00:15:58.600
in ecology but across disciplines.

00:15:58.610 --> 00:16:01.620
In the dawn of everything, David Graber and David Wen

00:16:01.620 --> 00:16:04.600
grau reconsider the narrative of human history.

00:16:04.610 --> 00:16:07.660
So this history is usually discussed as a straight line from hunter

00:16:07.660 --> 00:16:12.180
-gatherer society to agricultural revolution to industrial revolution to

00:16:12.180 --> 00:16:12.600
now.

00:16:12.610 --> 00:16:16.050
The Davids challenge this notion and point out how during the

00:16:16.050 --> 00:16:19.220
long time where humans were thought to be hunter-gather

00:16:19.220 --> 00:16:21.240
ers, there's not too much evidence of what they were

00:16:21.240 --> 00:16:24.380
doing, so it's easy to spin a bunch of narratives

00:16:24.380 --> 00:16:25.600
on top of that.

00:16:25.610 --> 00:16:28.470
But if you do look at the evidence, there seems to

00:16:28.470 --> 00:16:30.600
be a plurality of societal forms.

00:16:30.610 --> 00:16:33.710
So there are hunter-gatherer societies, but also

00:16:33.710 --> 00:16:37.600
nomadic farmers or chiefdoms or different combinations of this

00:16:37.600 --> 00:16:40.600
depending on seasonality.

00:16:40.610 --> 00:16:43.580
So they say, maybe the real question is, how did

00:16:43.580 --> 00:16:44.600
we get stuck?

00:16:44.610 --> 00:16:47.600
How did we end up in one single mode?

00:16:47.610 --> 00:16:54.930
Wendell Berry is another one of my favorite writers and

00:16:54.930 --> 00:16:56.600
a lifelong farmer.

00:16:56.610 --> 00:17:00.220
And he talks about the importance of diversity to farming, both

00:17:00.220 --> 00:17:03.900
at a local level where a diversity of crops is needed to

00:17:03.900 --> 00:17:07.600
sustain soil, but also at a global level where each farm

00:17:07.600 --> 00:17:10.970
being in harmony with the land lends to a diversity of

00:17:10.970 --> 00:17:13.100
ways of doing farming, as opposed to a cash crop or

00:17:13.330 --> 00:17:18.030
industrialized farming that treats all land as the same and therefore

00:17:18.030 --> 00:17:19.600
depletes it.

00:17:23.610 --> 00:17:26.990
And in this essay, Maria and Robin, who I think

00:17:26.990 --> 00:17:31.680
is here today, write that ecologists know that diversity is

00:17:31.740 --> 00:17:32.600
resilient.

00:17:32.610 --> 00:17:35.600
I think this concept goes beyond ecology.

00:17:35.610 --> 00:17:38.600
I think this is true of the internet as well.

00:17:38.610 --> 00:17:41.510
An internet where one data center going down means the web goes

00:17:41.510 --> 00:17:46.400
down is not resilient, and where one platform insidifying

00:17:46.400 --> 00:17:53.580
means everyone's experiences are insidified is not resilient.

00:17:53.610 --> 00:17:56.230
So I think the key for app protocol to survive as a

00:17:56.230 --> 00:18:00.600
protocol and ecosystem is for us to be resilient by supporting the

00:18:00.600 --> 00:18:03.900
necessary diversity of infrastructures, technologies, social networks, and

00:18:03.940 --> 00:18:05.600
communities that human life demands.

00:18:05.610 --> 00:18:11.060
Right now, this lack of diversity online is a really strongly

00:18:11.060 --> 00:18:12.600
felt experience.

00:18:12.610 --> 00:18:15.430
In the physical world, your library doesn't look or feel

00:18:15.430 --> 00:18:18.980
like your kitchen, your bedroom, your school, your patio

00:18:18.980 --> 00:18:19.600
, etc.

00:18:19.610 --> 00:18:22.600
But online, this is absolutely the case.

00:18:22.610 --> 00:18:25.510
My hope is that with app protocol, we can shape our

00:18:25.510 --> 00:18:29.320
digital habitats with as much agency as we can our physical ones

00:18:29.320 --> 00:18:29.600
.

00:18:29.610 --> 00:18:37.600
So in the real world of technology, Ursula M.

00:18:37.600 --> 00:18:40.050
Franklin talks about how hard it is to define technology as a

00:18:40.050 --> 00:18:40.590
concept.

00:18:40.610 --> 00:18:44.010
However, one definition we might be able to agree upon is

00:18:44.010 --> 00:18:46.600
technology as a way of doing something.

00:18:46.610 --> 00:18:49.470
So, if the current state of the web is just one

00:18:49.470 --> 00:18:53.180
way of doing the social internet, then let's build the

00:18:53.180 --> 00:18:55.600
social internet differently.

00:18:55.610 --> 00:18:57.600
Thank you.

00:18:57.610 --> 00:19:03.040
Let's give a round of applause.
